Reading Discussion: Linear Regression

Intro to Correlation and Linear Regression

we start with a scatterplot, an x and a y

Examples: mpg data

ggplot(mpg, aes(x=displ, y=hwy))+
  geom_jitter()+
  theme_classic()

Key qualities of a relationship

  1. form/shape: here in 120, we only do linear relationships. BBut there are many kinds, exponential, logisticm polonomial, etc.

  2. directoin: positive or negative, first cty vs hwy is positive, both go up together, on the other hand, displacement and hwy is a negative relatinosihp

  3. stength: the first graph is tighter, if it comes as close as possible to a line then it is very strong

Linear correlation coefficient: r

the correlation coefficient r measures the strength and the direction of the relationship,

if r is close to 1 then there is a strong positive relationship. if r is close to -1 then there is a strong negative relationsip. if r is close to 0 then there is no relationship.

fair warning: r only describes linear relationships. Ex on board: a semi circle can have a relatinship but the r can still be 0. a horizontal line also has a relationship but r is still 0. (y is not affected by x). Two lines, one has a steeper slope, both have corelation coefficient of 1.

properties of r

  • r is alwyas between -1< r <1
  • does not matter which is x which is y
  • r does not depend on units

Least Squares Equation

y = 41 + 0.59x

its a line, y = mx+b

in stats we use differnet letts

The equation

yhat = b_1 *x + b_0

  • b_1 is the slope

  • b_0 is the intercept

Example

# in R we use lm as linear model 

lm(hwy~cty, data = mpg)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = hwy ~ cty, data = mpg)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)          cty  
##       0.892        1.337
cor(mpg$cty, mpg$hwy) # tells you r
## [1] 0.9559159
ggplot(mpg, aes(x=cty, y=hwy))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
  theme_classic()

# observations

  • the ~ has a special meaning: hwy is a function of cty. Note that y comes first: here thats why fuel efficiency
  • were prediciting why based on city

chalange

lm(cty~displ, data = mpg)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = cty ~ displ, data = mpg)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        displ  
##       25.99        -2.63
cor(mpg$cty, mpg$displ) # tells you r
## [1] -0.798524
ggplot(mpg, aes(x=cty, y=displ))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
  theme_classic()
